# Real-time First (Web)

The default for every page in this app is **real-time over websockets, with the HTTP fetch as the on-mount/on-activate sync**. The user should never need to refresh to see something the server already knows about.

## The pattern

For any page or component that displays state which can change while the user is looking at it, you wire **two** things:

1. **HTTP fetch** on mount / activation — gets the user "caught up" to the current server state. This is the source of truth at first paint.
2. **Websocket subscription** while the page is alive — keeps that local state in sync as the server emits events.

Both are required. Neither alone is enough:

- HTTP-only → user has to refresh to see new replies, invites, badge counts, etc.
- Socket-only → user opens the page, sees nothing until the next event lands.

## How to wire it

Use the `usePresence()` composable (`composables/usePresence.ts`). It owns the singleton socket, exposes typed callback registries (`addPostsCallback`, `addCrewCallback`, `addGroupInviteCallback`, `addNotificationsCallback`, `addOnlineFeedCallback`, `addSpacesCallback`, `addRadioCallback`, `addMessagesCallback`, …), and wires reconnect / cross-tab fan-out automatically. Don't open your own socket.

```ts
const { addGroupInviteCallback, removeGroupInviteCallback } = usePresence()

const cb = {
  onReceived: (payload) => { /* patch local state in place */ },
  onUpdated:  (payload) => { /* patch local state in place */ },
}

onMounted(() => addGroupInviteCallback(cb))
onBeforeUnmount(() => removeGroupInviteCallback(cb))
```

### When the page also has subscription-style data

For posts, articles, spaces, radio, etc., the gateway requires the client to **subscribe** to a room/topic before it gets events. Always pair `subscribe*` with `unsubscribe*`:

```ts
onMounted(() => {
  addPostsCallback(postsCb)
  if (postId.value) subscribePosts([postId.value])
})
watch(() => postId.value, (pid, prev) => {
  if (prev) unsubscribePosts([prev])
  if (pid) subscribePosts([pid])
})
onBeforeUnmount(() => {
  removePostsCallback(postsCb)
  if (postId.value) unsubscribePosts([postId.value])
})
```

### onActivated, not just onMounted

For pages inside `<KeepAlive>` (most app routes), use `onActivated` to **also re-fetch** when the user navigates back to the page. The socket subscription stays alive, but the page may have missed events while it was inactive — a fresh fetch closes that gap.

```ts
onActivated(async () => {
  await fetchList({ forceRefresh: true })
})
```

## What socket events should do to local state

Patch in place, don't refetch. The server's socket payload is the same DTO as the HTTP response, so you can splice it into your local `ref`/`useState` directly:

```ts
const cb: NotificationsCallback = {
  onUpdated: (payload) => {
    notifications.value = notifications.value.map((n) =>
      n.id === payload.notification.id ? { ...n, ...payload.notification } : n,
    )
  },
}
```

Refetch only when the event tells you the local cache can't be patched (deletion of an unknown entity, structural reordering, etc.).

## Optimistic UI

When the **viewer** initiated the change (sent an invite, posted a comment, accepted/declined), update local state optimistically right after the HTTP call resolves. Don't wait for the round-trip socket echo — but DO let the socket event arrive harmlessly (your reducer must be idempotent and de-dupe by id).

## What does NOT need socket wiring

- Static / marketing pages (`/`, `/about`, `/tiers`, `/privacy`, …).
- Pages whose content is fully derived from URL params and never mutated server-side mid-session (e.g. a static article archive).
- One-shot flows that close immediately (composer dialogs, confirm modals).

If you skip socket wiring for a page that displays mutable state, leave a one-line comment explaining why. That's the contract that keeps the real-time surface honest.

## API contract

The other side of this lives in the API repo: `menofhunger-api/.cursor/rules/60-realtime-first.mdc` requires every state-changing service to emit through `PresenceRealtimeService`. If a feature ships without a backend emit, the front-end work is wasted — flag it before writing the page.

